HEADWORD: Endorhiza
<hw>En`do*rhi"za</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Endorhiz⟦ae⟧</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/
within + <?/ root.]</ety> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>Any monocotyledonous
plant; -- so named because many monocotyledons have an endorhizal
embryo.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <ex>Endorhiza</ex> was proposed by Richard as a
substitute for the term <xex>endogen</xex>, and <xex>exorhiza</xex> as a
substitute for the term <xex>exogen</xex>; but they have not been
generally adopted.</note></p>

